{
  "id": "019d2de2-bbbb-7791-b050-84b5894e9b8d",
  "content": "# Forgetting Policy Research: Production Systems Analysis (March 2026)\n\n## Redis Agent Memory Server (Deep Dive)\n\n### 4 Forgetting Policies\n1. **Age-based**: `FORGETTING_MAX_AGE_DAYS` (default 90). Hard delete after absolute age threshold.\n2. **Inactivity-based**: `FORGETTING_MAX_INACTIVE_DAYS` (default 7 per config page, 30 per docs). Delete if not accessed within window.\n3. **Combined (age + inactivity)**: Dual threshold — must be BOTH old AND inactive, UNLESS age exceeds `max_age_days * hard_age_multiplier` (default 12.0x = ~3 years), in which case hard-delete regardless.\n4. **Budget-based**: `FORGETTING_BUDGET_KEEP_TOP_N` (default 1000). Ranks by recency composite score, keeps top N.\n\n### Budget Scoring Composite Function (from source code)\n```\nsemantic_weight: 0.0  (budget ignores similarity)\nrecency_weight: 1.0\nfreshness_weight: 0.6  (weight on last_accessed recency)\nnovelty_weight: 0.4    (weight on created_at recency)\nhalf_life_last_access_days: 7.0\nhalf_life_created_days: 30.0\n```\nUses `rerank_with_recency()` — exponential decay with configurable half-lives. Memories outside top N deleted.\n\n### Pinning: `pinned=True` flag or `pinned_ids` set. Pinned memories NEVER deleted regardless of policy.\n\n### Background Worker: Docket (Redis-based task scheduler). `periodic_forget_long_term_memories` registered as Perpetual task. Default interval: 60 minutes. Requires separate `task-worker` process. Compaction runs every 10 minutes.\n\n### Compaction: Progressive summarization via LLM. Keeps ~40% recent messages, summarizes older ones into anchor state. Token allocation: 5-12.5% reserved for summaries depending on model size. No explicit deduplication — relies on LLM semantic compression.\n\n### Key limitation: Forgetting DISABLED by default. No per-namespace/per-scope config — global only.\n\n## Zep/Graphiti Temporal Knowledge Graph\n- Bi-temporal model: event time (T) + ingestion time (T')\n- 4 timestamps per edge: t'_created, t'_expired, t_valid, t_invalid\n- Invalidation, NOT deletion: contradicted edges get `t_invalid` set to the `t_valid` of the invalidating edge\n- LLM compares new edges against semantically related existing edges for contradiction detection\n- No compaction/pruning — preserves full history with temporal markers\n- Episode subgraph (raw data) + Semantic Entity subgraph (extracted knowledge) + Community subgraph (clusters)\n\n## Mem0 Write-Time Deduplication\n- LLM extracts facts → embedding similarity check → LLM conflict resolution (add/update/noop)\n- Similarity threshold ~0.85 triggers merge consideration, ~0.9 for dedup clusters\n- `infer=True` (default): runs conflict resolution. `infer=False`: raw storage, duplicates land\n- Consolidation cuts storage 60%, raises retrieval precision 22%\n- No documented forgetting/expiration policies — focuses on write-time intelligence\n\n## Compaction Strategies Comparison\n1. **Redis**: LLM progressive summarization (anchored iterative — extend, don't regenerate)\n2. **Mem0**: Write-time dedup prevents accumulation\n3. **Zep**: No compaction — temporal invalidation preserves history\n4. **Factory pattern**: Anchor with 4 fields (intent, changes, decisions, next steps). 4.04 accuracy vs Anthropic 3.74\n5. **Knowledge Objects (KO paper)**: Anti-compaction — external fact storage, never compress. 60% knowledge loss documented with cascading compaction.\n\n## Safety Rails\n- Redis: `pinned=True` flag, `pinned_ids` parameter\n- EU AI Act: 10-year audit trail for high-risk AI systems (enforceable Aug 2026)\n- GDPR: Right to erasure conflicts with retention — anonymize personal data, keep metadata\n- MemOS: Multi-level permission control + operation auditing for memory access\n- Recommendation: Importance >= 0.7 should never auto-delete (MaRS taxonomy)\n\n## Gradual vs Cliff Forgetting\n- Ebbinghaus curve: `strength = importance * e^(-decay_rate * days_since_access)`\n- Decay rate inversely proportional to importance: `decay_rate = 0.16 * (1 - importance * 0.8)`\n- Pruning at strength <= 0.05 (gradual fade, not sudden cliff)\n- Access resets decay clock (reinforcement)\n- FadeMem dual-layer: Long-term (slow decay) + Short-term (fast decay)\n- Applied at search time, not storage time — lazy evaluation\n\n## Background Worker Patterns\n- Redis: Docket periodic task, 60min default, separate worker process required\n- Supabase: Scheduled SQL DELETE, daily\n- LangGraph: Platform-managed sweep at configurable intervals\n- Decay-at-search-time: No background worker needed, but doesn't reclaim storage",
